{
  "texts": [
    "The pentagon equations have a finite number of solutions, a result known as the Ocneanu rigidity and a given fusion ring may not even admit a single solution [11].",
    "It is an open question to systematically classify fusion categories, which appears much richer than the classification of discrete groups.Adjoint structure and unitarity.",
    "So far we have avoided dwelling upon an important property of the QFTs that we consider here, namely unitarity.",
    "Correspondingly, non-invertible TDLs in a unitary QFT are described by a unitary fusion category.",
    "At the level of the data for the fusion category introduced above, unitarity is encoded in the adjoint structure of the morphism spaces, which specifies an anti-linear map,†: Hom C (L, L ′) → Hom C (L ′, L)(2.8)for all L, L ′ ∈ C. The map † defines a bilinear form via the correlation function ⟨u † v⟩ of junction vectors u, v ∈ Hom C (L, L ′)."
  ]
}